<div class="post-date">21 October 2007</div>
<h2><a href="http://www.ontheriversedge.com/index.php?id=1297" title="Erie Canal locks at Lockport, New York"> Erie Canal locks at Lockport, New York</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


        
	<p>Probably the biggest challenge of building the Erie Canal was finding a way down the <a href="http://www.escarpment.org/">Niagara Escarpment</a> &#8212; the same steep cliff the Niagara Falls originally flowed over. </p>

	<p>The builder&#8217;s solution was a series of five locks to drop canal boats more than 50 feet at Lockport. They later replaced the quint locks with a pair of huge locks that serves today. The old locks are now a spillway sometimes called Lockport Falls.</p>

	<p><img src="/images/481t.jpg" style="width:120px;height:160px;" alt="vacation-Monday---17.jpg" /></p>

<div class="line"></div>

<div class="smallcat">Posted in </div>
<div class="smalluser"> by <a rel="author" href="http://www.ontheriversedge.com/index.php?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a></div>
<div class="smallcomments"><a href="http://www.ontheriversedge.com/index.php?id=1297#comment"  class="comments_invite">Comment</a></div>
<div class="clear"></div>
</div>

      




